                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hmmm...
<br />

<br />
One thing that allways gets me is the "uber" principle.  Everyone seems to think that it is sooo important to be "uber" with the best stats, focus effects and whatnot.  What about the "uber" feeling of accomplishing something?  The fact that you passed to a guildie who may need worse than you is more important than being "uber", dont you think?  Also, the shawl is a major accomplishment, up there with your epic, do the grind and take pride in the fact that you will have something that is far more SIGNIFICANT than something you won in a roll.  Dont get me wrong, its great to take on a mob, figure out a tactic, and get that great loot from the kill, but its nothing compared to actually taking the time and care to build something.  When I see two toons, one with a Prayer Shawl and one who was given a peice maybe twice as good (on the "uber" scale), I would far prefer to group with the Prayer Shawl holder.  Why?  Well...  He takes care in his toon, pride in his play and probably plays his character far better then the one who was given something.
<br />

<br />
Just my opinion...
<br />

<br />
Enkidoo
<br />
