                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When I see two toons, one with a Prayer Shawl and one who was given a peice maybe twice as good (on the "uber" scale), I would far prefer to group with the Prayer Shawl holder. Why? Well... He takes care in his toon, pride in his play and probably plays his character far better then the one who was given something. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
And exactly what pieces are there that are "twice as good (on the "uber" scale)"  or, heck, that are even -comparable- that can be "given" to a character?  I wore a <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/item.html?id=55216" target="_blank" class="postlink">Shawl of the Firewalker</a> for a good long time because there is a serious shortage of good, DROPPABLE shoulders.   It's not as if you can just twink someone with a piece of gear that's "twice as good as the shawl".
<br />

<br />
That said, I could make a case that A) A lot of people who don't give a damn about their character see the shawl as an "easy" way to get FT3. (You'd be surprised at how many of these there are. I know people who do this quest for their twinks.) and B) Someone who spent a lot of time farming greens and clicking "combine" may simply have spent more time doing that than learning how to play his or her character in difficult situations.
<br />

<br />
Neither of those assertions is any more true or less true than yours.
<br />

<br />
The moral of this story is that you can't assume anything about someone either way just because they have or do not have a given piece of gear.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
